Autonomous Vehicle Path Planning using Q-Learning

Source:
https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1742-6596/2128/1/012018/pdf

Algorithm Description

State Space

The state space is a 3-dimensional array in the shape (𝑖, 𝑗, 𝑘); where 𝑖 represents the position with respect to the 𝑥 dimension, 𝑗 the position with respect to the 𝑦 dimension, and 𝑘 the third dimension represents what the sensors are seeing. In the model’s current state 𝑘 has eight sensors each with 2 possible states (0 = 𝑛𝑜 𝑜𝑏𝑠𝑡𝑎𝑐𝑙𝑒, 1 = 𝑜𝑏𝑠𝑡𝑎𝑐𝑙𝑒 detected) so all in all .

e.g. in a 6 𝑚 𝑥 6 𝑚 space, which was discretized into steps of 0.25 m in each direction the size of the state space would be (25,25,256) with 160000 states.

==Question: Why each grid have obstacle states?
Answer: For each grid the actor stays, the remaining 255 grids can be distributed with obstacles. So (25, 25, 256) is needed to model all the possibilities.

Question: For humans, we don’t need to know all the possibilities to plan a path. We only need to know the target and adjust our route based on observed obstacles one by one.

Questions: If we change 256 to (25, 25), it will be better presentable, won't it?

Action Space

North, East, South, and West, each step is a grid. It's a one dimensional array.
Question: For humans, our action could be one step several grids. So, can the step be two dimension, the second dimension describes how many grids in the step.

==Question: The direction should also includes the diagonal direction.

Question: The action shall also include Acceleration.

Rewards

Table 1. Rewards for various behaviors given to the agent.

Behavior Reward
Collision -20
Reach the target 20
Go out of bounds -20
Move a step -1
Backtracking -20

Note: Since the actor can only move in four directions, it needs to choose the best reward behavior, in most cases, it's "Move a step".

Hyperparameter

• α is the learning rate of the algorithm which controls how big of a change the reward is going to
affect the new value of Q.
• γ is the discount factor of the expected future reward for taking the next best action.
• ε is the ratio of exploration vs exploitation meaning, how often does the algorithm try new things
versus using the information it has already learned, an epsilon of 0.1 means the algorithm will
try new things 10% of the time and will exploit its known values 90% of the time.

Note: For ε , at each step use ε to decide an random choice whether to use Q function to select the action or use random action.

Experiments and results

Static Environment Experiment.

The agent was placed at a stationary starting position with a stationary goal. In approximately 750
episodes the agent could reach the goal in the optimal number of steps. At 1000 episodes it could reach the goal using the shortest path from any starting position.

Note: It deals with static limited environment well.

Dynamic Environment Experiment

after the addition of the proximity sensors, the goal was to prove whether or not Q-learning could actually learn obstacle avoidance, instead of simply memorising a couple of states where it has collided with a stationary obstacle and received a penalty.

Question: This is a trial and conclusion method, but why? Need theoretical analysis.

Answer: This is due to NN's all function approximation capability. [Liangxiao Li] However, by using environment and actor to generate training data to form the avoiding path maybe inefficient as it lacks descriptive model and lack the support supervised learning success story support. CNN, LSTM and transformer technique may help. Relative keywords may include segmentation.

Question: This experiment doesn't support moving obstacles.
Answer: So, for moving obstacles, the complexity will be much higher. It means simple Q-Learning can't tackle such problems, measures need to be taken to reduce the complexity.

Table 2. Hyperparameters of each experiment
Parameter Description Value in Experiment 1st 2nd
𝒏𝒐𝒃𝒔𝒕 Number of obstacles 1 (stationary) 3 (randomized)
𝒃𝒐𝒖𝒏𝒅𝒂𝒓𝒚𝑿 Size of the workspace the X- Direction in meters 6 4

𝒏𝒔𝒆𝒏𝒔𝒐𝒓𝒔 Number of proximity sensors 0 8

𝜺 Explore vs Exploit 0.1 0.1

Note: the bold part is different form static experiment.

The randomized obstacles exponentially increased the system’s complexity, as the environment itself had various configurations, the number of possible environments is based on the combination of possible obstacle configurations multiplied by the possible agent configurations in the remaining spaces.

This resulted in an increased training time, with some episodes lasting infinitely so a cut-off was added to ensure that if the agent was cornered by 2 obstacles it would have the possibility to try again in a new environment.

If it could not start the next episode, after 9400 episodes as the simulation approximately took
26 hours to reach that point, the cut-off was modified to be 5000 steps/episode instead.

Note: It suggests the complexity of the task using RL. More research need to be done to make RL capable for the configuration.

Also, it is important to note a tweak was added to prevent the agent from looping between two states, if the previous state were equal to the next state it would receive a penalty and negative -20 reward this is referred to as backtracking in Table 1.

Note: It suggests that Q-learning should not support backtracking, or the episode will go to dead loop.

The tweak increased training time, however, it created a controller which would not infinitely loop
between two states randomly, which is a favorable outcome.

Question: Why does it increase the training time? No answer in the paper.

Figure 10 shows the testing data as the previous figure for the last 50 tests, showcasing a clear
improvement over the first 150 tests especially around the last 20 tests (from episode 18000 to 20000).

Conclusion

• The first test showcased optimal path planning in a static environment as the robot was always
successful in finding the shortest path from any starting position.
• The second test showcased the complexity of the problem, the algorithm would have
eventually converged if it was allowed enough training time using better simulating hardware.
• The Q-Learning approach shows a clear advantage where it doesn’t require a priori
information or maps to solve the path planning problem, whereas other algorithms solely rely
on accurate maps of the environment like RRT*.

Note: This paper proved the validity and efficiency of path planning with Q-Learning in static environment. It has also proved the feasibility of Obstacle Avoidance using Q-Learning. However, it has also proved the high computational cost and complexity to tackle dynamic problems using Q-Learning.

Note:This algorithm needs to be improved with much effort to tackle problems more similar to real world problems such as:

  1. moving obstacle;
  2. various configuration of obstacle.
  3. Acceleration of actor.
  4. Diagonal direction movement.
